name: acetamide, n-(4-hydroxyphenyl)

The melting point of a compound is influenced by several factors, including the presence of functional groups and their intermolecular interactions. In the case of N-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetamide, also known as paracetamol, we can analyze the impact of the following functional groups on the melting point based on related compounds: 
- Basic phenol unit: Similar to phenol which has a melting point of 43°C, the hydroxyl group (-OH) can form hydrogen bonds, raising the melting point significantly. Increment estimate: +100°C due to hydrogen bonding capacity and rigidity of the aromatic ring.
- Acetamide group: Compared to acetic acid (melting point 16°C), the amide group can also engage in hydrogen bonding, but it is more electronically delocalized over the amide functionality, which increases the melting point. - Aromatic-amide interaction: The intramolecular hydrogen bonding between the amide NH and the hydroxyl group on the aromatic ring further raises the melting point due to the stability it imparts. Increment estimate: +30°C.
Based on these considerations, the predicted melting point would be a sum of the base melting point of phenol and the incremental increases due to each functional group.

Phenol base unit melting point: 43°C.
Hydroxy group increment: +100°C.
Acetamide group increment: +70°C.
Aromatic-amide interaction increment: +30°C.
Predicted melting point: 43 + 100 + 70 + 30 = 243°C
